The worst part about this certificate program is definitely the peer-review aspect. Sometimes it will take days for my assignments to be graded and it is a terrible experience to have your work reviewed by someone who does not take it seriously. Sometimes people will even give you all zeros for no reason, or give entirely random grades, then you need to resubmit and wait another few days/hours for a grade. I should have been done with this course a long time ago but I must wait for others to grade my work. I also had someone respond inappropriately to one of my assignments and we are not able to report the peers who review our work. The capstone course makes it all worse because this one has the most peer-graded assignments out of all the courses in this certificate.

The information is great, the platform is terrible. I loved learning from Google PM's, I love the practice activities, and the scinarios the teachers used, but I hated the peer reviewd documents. I have ben an educator for 12 years prior to my career move and everything I know to be true about assessment was ignored in this entire 6 course program. Peer reviews are incredably frustrating. One peer accesses your work and give you great marks with awesome feedback. The next person has trouble opening your document so they give you all 0's and you have to start again. This occured for most of my work in this program. I spent the last week of my "learning" begging my peers to review my work in the discussion boards. On average, I would say that I had to resubmit each one of my peer reviewd assignments 3 times. Then there was the posting in the discussion board and "returning the favor" by grading even more of my peer's work. This is not a system that works. With the course fee being what it is, I'd prefer to have my work graded by instructors. Lastly, when I did finish a course I was prompted by Coursera to "verify my ID." I've been verifying my ID for completed coursrses for weeks now, every time I log in, and the promt never goes away. So I figured when I did complete the course, it would be a surprise what name appeared on my certificate. I've completed and I'm being prompted now to "purchase certificate." Clicking on that button, again, does nothing. I've been doing this for 3 days. I don't know how much the purchase is, who's name (if any) will be on it, or how long it will take to get it. I begin a new career in July and I thought starting this course in late April would be enough time to complete it and provide my new employer with certification. I worked really hard to get the classwork done quickly, little did I know that the hardest and most time consuming part of the process was just getting Coursera to work. Also, don't count on the moble app to be any help. As long as you have the work posted, it shows you have completed 100%. This is great until you log into the website and it says 97% and tells you that you failed 3 more of your peer reviewed assignments (with feedback saying "I can't access your PDF or Google Doc." Then the cycle continues: re-posting, begging for help in the discussion board, returning the favor of grading MORE of your peers work, praying people who can't access your work don't fail you (and just skip past yours). It is infuriating! I am a Google Certified Educator and I loved that program. I learned so much! I was really hopeful that this learning would be of the same quality. Sadly, it was not.

The other courses were mostly good, but I honestly don't know what Google were thinking with this course.It's supposed to give you a full life-cycle experience and a project portfolio that you can present to employers. I'd be embarrassed to show this to a high school teacher. The depth of involvement is skimpy to say the least while the document formats are just plain amateur - they look like someone's high school project.The biggest failure is the planning section: you build out the timeline using total time duration estimates only. There's no effort duration, no dependency analysis, no critical path. You end up having to allocate 2 weeks on your path for a task that would have a 30 minute effort duration. And since the planning is entirely linear, the timeline ends up at something like 5 months instead of the 3 or 4 weeks this would probably take.This alone is a huge failure - being able to plan a project timeline out properly is one of the most critical skills in PM, I was looking forward to being guided through a proper hands-on example.Similarly, the close-out just involves adding a couple of paragraphs to an impact report. The level of testing is really low, and there is a ridiculous amount of cheating going on. When grading peers, you see the same assignment being submitted over and over.The content has some odd examples - you are asked to escalate a problem to a senior stakeholder after learning a contract condition will change. When you do a few seconds of maths, you realise the new contract will nearly halve the contract cost ... there's no problem to escalate.Another part has you making confidence level estimates on tasks, based on the levels of experience of people who aren't involved in the task (the waiting staff have no experience of electrical wiring or POS system upgrades ....).The course is useful for completing the certificate, but that's about it.

While there is certainly some insightful knowledge to be gained from this course, overall, it feels like a low education level style. The instruction is clear, mostly to the point, the instructors are effective communicators and the capstone project covers what was learned. However, the tasks and other demonstrations of knowledge are so easy it almost feels insignificant and some points. More so, when grading peer work, it is obvious some people put in zero effort because they will submit incomplete projects or the wrong project entirely, most likely in the hopes someone is too lazy to look at their work. The discussion boards are pointless and most people’s responses are as simple as “hi.” I am leaving this course with a solid foundational knowledge of project management but I am doubting the legitimacy behind it and concerned whether any employer will see this course as a strong demonstration of my intelligence.

The content is good but the grading system is terrible. I could bet money that some people submit reviews without even opening the linked documents. I've gotten points taken off for missing content that was very clearly included, labeled, color-coded, and in bold. I've recieved wildly different scores on the exact same assignment from multiple people. I tested this out because one of my assignments I failed the first time for having components marked missing that were 100% there. I re-submitted the exact same assignment with no changes-- got a 100% that time. Plus if you get a poor grade you have to resubmit and HOPE someone reveiws your work, because if nobody reviews it, you just sit in limbo unable to complete the course. The idea of these courses is fantastic, but peer-grading in this manner just encourages people to click random points and not actually provide legitimate feedback. That defeats the whole purpose of having graded written work. And if that's the way it will go, they should just eliminate peer-reviewed work in favor of the quizzes and tests, etc. Or maybe have a project that you have to submit at the end that is reviewed by a professional or something.

The curriculum was the right level of detail (for me, anyway) and the pedagogy was excellent. The entire 6-course series was very well-crafted. I especially appreciated the inclusive and non-judgmental discussions of how to manage people's differing learning and communication styles.  I also appreciated that way that respect was modeled in the ways the material was presented. This was my first experience with  MOOC and it took some getting used to the idea of peer-review assignments; people tend to grade based on their personal interpretation of the brief. I do obviously understand the necessity of peer-review over instructor grading, so having said that I think it was as well-handled as possible. I would definitely recommend this course to others who are seeking knowledge of project management.

This course was good, but the greatest struggle I had with all of these courses were the peer graded assignments. I appreciate that items were actually graded by a real person, but quite a few people were not able to grade on a basic level. They would grade 0s, rather than flag the submission if they could not access the document (most of the time, the assignment was there, they were just looking for an attachment rather than a  link).  I needed to resubmit a few assignments without making any changes, simply because a peer grader could not find my initial submission. If one grader is giving all points, but a second grader gives no points, an improvement might be that the submission gets flagged for a moderator, or automatically go to a third peer grader so that items will get graded quicker...just a suggestion.Otherwise, I think the presenters, content, and worksheets were all very well made. I saved all of the documents, and look forward to potentially using them as things come up in work, or if I ever have a future career in Project Management.
